In Java, a collection of objects represents a group of individual elements treated as a single unit. Java provides a powerful and flexible Collection Framework (introduced in JDK 1.2) to store, manipulate, and iterate over groups of objects efficiently.

Collection Framework is located in the java.util package and consists of:
a. Collection Interface (java.util.Collection): root interface for List, Set, Queue
b. Map Interface (java.util.Map): root interface for key-value pairs

-> Methods to Iterate Through Collection Objects in Java
Method 1: Using an enhanced for loop 
The enhanced for loop is the simplest and most readable way to iterate through a collection.
Syntax used :
for (datatype variable: collection) {
    // statements
}

import java.util.*;
​
class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
​
        // Declaring the ArrayList
        Collection<String> gfg = new ArrayList<>();
​
        // Adding elements
        gfg.add("Abhishek Rout");
        gfg.add("Vaibhav Kamble");
        gfg.add("Anupam Kumar");
​
        // Iterating using enhanced for loop
        for (String name : gfg) {
            System.out.println("Name : " + name);
        }
    }
}

Output
Name : Abhishek Rout
Name : Vaibhav Kamble
Name : Anupam Kumar

a. Works with all Iterable collections
b. Cannot modify the collection while iterating
c. Best for read-only traversal

Method 2: Using Iterator Interface
The Iterator interface provides controlled iteration and allows element removal during traversal.
Syntax used :
Iterator<Type> iterator = collection.iterator();
while (iterator.hasNext()) {
    Type element = iterator.next();
}

import java.util.*;
​class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
​
        // Declaring the LinkedList
        LinkedList<String> gfg = new LinkedList<>();
​
        // Adding elements
        gfg.add("Abhishek Rout");
        gfg.add("Vaibhav Kamble");
        gfg.add("Anupam Kumar");
​
        // Using Iterator with for loop
        System.out.println("Using For Loop");
        for (Iterator<String> it = gfg.iterator(); it.hasNext(); ) {
            System.out.println("Name : " + it.next());
        }
​
        // Using Iterator with while loop
        System.out.println("\nUsing While Loop");
        Iterator<String> it = gfg.iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) {
            System.out.println("Name : " + it.next());
        }
    }
}

Output
Using For Loop
Name : Abhishek Rout
Name : Vaibhav Kamble
Name : Anupam Kumar

Using While Loop
Name : Abhishek Rout
Name : Vaibhav Kamble
Name : Anupam Kumar

a. Allows safe removal using iterator.remove()
b. Preferred when modifying collections
c. More flexible than enhanced for loop

-> Method 3: Using Simple For Loop (Index-Based Iteration)
This approach is applicable only for indexed collections like List, ArrayList, Vector.
Syntax used :
for (int i = 0; i < collection.size(); i++) {
    collection.get(i);
}

import java.util.*;
​
class GFG{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
​
        // Declaring the Vector
        Vector<String> gfg = new Vector<>();
​
        // Adding elements
        gfg.add("Abhishek Rout");
        gfg.add("Vaibhav Kamble");
        gfg.add("Anupam Kumar");
​
        // Iterating using simple for loop
        for (int i = 0; i < gfg.size(); i++) {
            System.out.println("Name " + (i + 1) + ": " + gfg.get(i));
        }
    }
}

Output
Name 1: Abhishek Rout
Name 2: Vaibhav Kamble
Name 3: Anupam Kumar

a. Allows access using index
b. Not applicable to Set or Queue
c. Less efficient for LinkedList

Method 4: Using forEach() Method (Java 8+)
Java 8 introduced the forEach() method, which uses lambda expressions and functional programming concepts.
Syntax used :
a. With Lambda Expression
collection.forEach(element -> {
    System.out.println(element);
});

b. With Method Reference
collection.forEach(System.out::println);

import java.util.*;
​
class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
​
        // Declaring the ArrayList
        ArrayList<String> gfg = new ArrayList<>();
​
        // Adding elements
        gfg.add("Abhishek Rout");
        gfg.add("Vaibhav Kamble");
        gfg.add("Anupam Kumar");
​
        // Using forEach with lambda
        System.out.println("With iterable");
        gfg.forEach(name -> {
            System.out.println("Name : " + name);
        });
​
        // Using forEach with method reference
        System.out.println("\nWithout iterable");
        gfg.forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}

Output
With iterable
Name : Abhishek Rout
Name : Vaibhav Kamble
Name : Anupam Kumar

Without iterable
Abhishek Rout
Vaibhav Kamble
Anupam Kumar

a. Clean and concise syntax
b. Best for functional-style programming
c. Not suitable when exception handling or breaking loops is required
